  "prompt": "What are some legal places to do graffiti in Seattle/Bothell?",
  "response": "In Seattle and Bothell, finding legal places to do graffiti often requires seeking out designated spaces or programs that encourage street art. Here are some options:\n\n### **Seattle:**\n1. **Seattle Graffiti Parks and Programs:**\n   - **Graffiti Cavern** (underneath the Pacific Place parking garage): A designated space for legal graffiti located in downtown Seattle.\n   - **The Seattle Mural Program**: Occasionally offers opportunities for artists to create murals in public spaces. Check with the Seattle Office of Arts & Culture for updates.\n   - **Wallingford Art Walk**: Some areas during the walk may allow temporary graffiti or street art.\n\n2. **Community Art Spaces:**\n   - **Urban ArtWorks**: A nonprofit that provides opportunities for artists to create murals and street art legally. They often collaborate with the city and local businesses.\n   - **The Vera Project**: While primarily a music and arts venue, they occasionally host events involving street art.\n\n3. **Business Collaborations:**\n   - Some businesses in Seattle allow artists to paint on their walls, especially in neighborhoods like Capitol Hill, Fremont, or the International District. Always get explicit permission before painting.\n\n### **Bothell:**\n1. **City Programs:**\n   - **Bothell Arts Commission**: Occasionally sponsors public art projects and may provide opportunities for legal graffiti or street art. Check their website or contact the city for updates.\n   - **Bothell Mural Project**: Some murals in the downtown area are community-driven and may offer opportunities for artists.\n\n2. **Parks and Public Spaces:**\n   - **Bothell\u2019s Parks and Recreation Department**: May host events or designate special areas for temporary art installations. Reach out to them for information.\n\n### **General Tips:**\n- **Permission is Key:** Even in designated areas, always confirm with the organization or property owner before starting any graffiti or street art.\n- **Events and Festivals:** Look for local art festivals or events that may include graffiti or street art components.\n- **Youth Programs:** Programs like **Urban ArtWorks** often involve young artists, so they can be a great way to get involved legally.\n\nRemember, illegal graffiti can lead to fines or criminal charges, so always seek out legal opportunities to express your art!",
  "temperature": 1.0,
